#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:21
msgid "Packaging Guide: testing installations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:23
msgid ""
"In this part of the packaging guide we will cover how to ensure your package "
"builds correctly by adding tests to it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:29
msgid "Checking an installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:31
msgid ""
"A package that *appears* to install successfully does not mean it is "
"actually installed correctly or will continue to work indefinitely. There "
"are a number of possible points of failure so Spack provides features for "
"checking the software along the way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:34
msgid ""
"Failures can occur during and after the installation process. The build may "
"start, but the software may not end up fully installed. The installed "
"software may not work at all, or may not work as expected. The software may "
"work after being installed, but due to changes on the system, may stop "
"working days, weeks, or months after being installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:39
msgid ""
"This section describes Spack's support for checks that can be performed "
"during and after its installation. The former checks are referred to as "
"``build-time tests`` and the latter as ``stand-alone (or smoke) tests``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:45
msgid "Build-time tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:47
msgid ""
"Spack infers the status of a build based on the contents of the install "
"prefix. Success is assumed if anything (e.g., a file or directory) is "
"written after ``install()`` completes. Otherwise, the build is assumed to "
"have failed. However, the presence of install prefix contents is not a "
"sufficient indicator of success so Spack supports the addition of tests that "
"can be performed during `spack install` processing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:52
msgid "Consider a simple autotools build using the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:54
msgid ""
"$ ./configure --prefix=/path/to/installation/prefix\n"
"$ make\n"
"$ make install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:60
msgid ""
"Standard Autotools and CMake do not write anything to the prefix from the "
"``configure`` and ``make`` commands. Files are only written from the ``make "
"install`` after the build completes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:65
msgid ""
"If you want to learn more about ``Autotools`` and ``CMake`` packages in "
"Spack, refer to :ref:`AutotoolsPackage <autotoolspackage>` and :ref:"
"`CMakePackage <cmakepackage>`, respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:67
msgid ""
"What can you do to check that the build is progressing satisfactorily? If "
"there are specific files and/or directories expected of a successful "
"installation, you can add basic, fast ``sanity checks``. You can also add "
"checks to be performed after one or more installation phases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:73
msgid ""
"Build-time tests are performed when the ``--test`` option is passed to "
"``spack install``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:77
msgid ""
"Build-time test failures result in a failed installation of the software."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:83
msgid "Adding sanity checks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:85
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, many builds of scientific software modify the installation "
"prefix **before** ``make install``. Builds like this can falsely report "
"success when an error occurs before the installation is complete. Simple "
"sanity checks can be used to identify files and/or directories that are "
"required of a successful installation. Spack checks for the presence of the "
"files and directories after ``install()`` runs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:90
msgid ""
"If any of the listed files or directories are missing, then the build will "
"fail and the install prefix will be removed. If they all exist, then Spack "
"considers the build successful from a sanity check perspective and keeps the "
"prefix in place."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:93
msgid ""
"For example, the sanity checks for the ``reframe`` package below specify "
"that eight paths must exist within the installation prefix after the "
"``install`` method completes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:95
msgid ""
"class Reframe(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    # sanity check\n"
"    sanity_check_is_file = [join_path(\"bin\", \"reframe\")]\n"
"    sanity_check_is_dir = [\n"
"        \"bin\", \n"
"        \"config\", \n"
"        \"docs\", \n"
"        \"reframe\", \n"
"        \"tutorials\",\n"
"        \"unittests\",\n"
"        \"cscs-checks\",\n"
"    ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:112
msgid ""
"When you run ``spack install`` with tests enabled, Spack will ensure that a "
"successfully installed package has the required files and/or directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:114
msgid "For example, running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:116
msgid "$ spack install --test=root reframe"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:120
msgid ""
"results in Spack checking that the installation created the following "
"**file**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:122
msgid "``self.prefix.bin.reframe``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:124
msgid "and the following **directories**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:126
msgid "``self.prefix.bin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:127
msgid "``self.prefix.config``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:128
msgid "``self.prefix.docs``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:129
msgid "``self.prefix.reframe``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:130
msgid "``self.prefix.tutorials``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:131
msgid "``self.prefix.unittests``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:132
msgid "``self.prefix.cscs-checks``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:134
msgid ""
"If **any** of these paths are missing, then Spack considers the installation "
"to have failed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:138
msgid ""
"You **MUST** use ``sanity_check_is_file`` to specify required files and "
"``sanity_check_is_dir`` for required directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:143
msgid "Adding installation phase tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:145
msgid ""
"Sometimes packages appear to build \"correctly\" only to have runtime "
"behavior issues discovered at a later stage, such as after a full software "
"stack relying on them has been built. Checks can be performed at different "
"phases of the package installation to possibly avoid these types of "
"problems. Some checks are built-in to different build systems, while others "
"will need to be added to the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:149
msgid ""
"Built-in installation phase tests are provided by packages inheriting from "
"select :ref:`build systems <build-systems>`, where naming conventions are "
"used to identify typical test identifiers for those systems. In general, you "
"won't need to add anything to your package to take advantage of these tests "
"if your software's build system complies with the convention; otherwise, "
"you'll want or need to override the post-phase method to perform other "
"checks."
msgstr ""

