#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:192
msgid ""
"For example, the ``Libelf`` package inherits from ``AutotoolsPackage`` and "
"its ``Makefile`` has a standard ``check`` target. So Spack will "
"automatically run ``make check`` after the ``build`` phase when it is "
"installed using the ``--test`` option, such as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:195
msgid "$ spack install --test=root libelf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:199
msgid ""
"In addition to overriding any built-in build system installation phase "
"tests, you can write your own install phase tests. You will need to use two "
"decorators for each phase test method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:202
msgid "``run_after``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:203
msgid "``on_package_attributes``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:205
msgid ""
"The first decorator tells Spack when in the installation process to run your "
"test method installation process; namely *after* the provided installation "
"phase. The second decorator tells Spack to only run the checks when the ``--"
"test`` option is provided on the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:210
msgid ""
"Be sure to place the directives above your test method in the order "
"``run_after`` *then* ``on_package_attributes``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:214
msgid ""
"You also want to be sure the package supports the phase you use in the "
"``run_after`` directive. For example, ``PackageBase`` only supports the "
"``install`` phase while the ``AutotoolsPackage`` and ``MakefilePackage`` "
"support both ``install`` and ``build`` phases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:217
msgid ""
"Assuming both ``build`` and ``install`` phases are available, you can add "
"additional checks to be performed after each of those phases based on the "
"skeleton provided below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:219
msgid ""
"class YourMakefilePackage(MakefilePackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    @run_after(\"build\")\n"
"    @on_package_attributes(run_tests=True)\n"
"    def check_build(self):\n"
"        # Add your custom post-build phase tests\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    @run_after(\"install\")\n"
"    @on_package_attributes(run_tests=True)\n"
"    def check_install(self):\n"
"        # Add your custom post-install phase tests\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:238
msgid ""
"You could also schedule work to be done **before** a given phase using the "
"``run_before`` decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:240
msgid ""
"By way of a concrete example, the ``reframe`` package mentioned previously "
"has a simple installation phase check that runs the installed executable. "
"The check is implemented as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:243
msgid ""
"class Reframe(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    # check if we can run reframe\n"
"    @run_after(\"install\")\n"
"    @on_package_attributes(run_tests=True)\n"
"    def check_list(self):\n"
"        with working_dir(self.stage.source_path):\n"
"            reframe = Executable(self.prefix.bin.reframe)\n"
"            reframe(\"-l\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:257
msgid "Checking build-time test results"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:259
msgid ""
"Checking the results of these tests after running ``spack install --test`` "
"can be done by viewing the spec's ``install-time-test-log.txt`` file whose "
"location will depend on whether the spec installed successfully."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:261
msgid ""
"A successful installation results in the build and stage logs being copied "
"to the ``.spack`` subdirectory of the spec's prefix. For example,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:264
msgid ""
"$ spack install --test=root zlib@1.2.13\n"
"...\n"
"[+] /home/user/spack/opt/spack/linux-rhel8-broadwell/gcc-10.3.1/zlib-1.2.13-"
"tehu6cbsujufa2tb6pu3xvc6echjstv6\n"
"$ cat /home/user/spack/opt/spack/linux-rhel8-broadwell/gcc-10.3.1/"
"zlib-1.2.13-tehu6cbsujufa2tb6pu3xvc6echjstv6/.spack/install-time-test-log.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:271
msgid ""
"If the installation fails due to build-time test failures, then both logs "
"will be left in the build stage directory as illustrated below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:273
msgid ""
"$ spack install --test=root zlib@1.2.13\n"
"...\n"
"See build log for details:\n"
"  /var/tmp/user/spack-stage/spack-stage-zlib-1.2.13-"
"lxfsivs4htfdewxe7hbi2b3tekj4make/spack-build-out.txt\n"
"\n"
"$ cat /var/tmp/user/spack-stage/spack-stage-zlib-1.2.13-"
"lxfsivs4htfdewxe7hbi2b3tekj4make/install-time-test-log.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:286
msgid "Stand-alone tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:288
msgid ""
"While build-time tests are integrated with the installation process, stand-"
"alone tests are expected to run days, weeks, even months after the software "
"is installed. The goal is to provide a mechanism for gaining confidence that "
"packages work as installed **and** *continue* to work as the underlying "
"software evolves. Packages can add and inherit stand-alone tests. The "
"``spack test`` command is used for stand-alone testing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:293
msgid "Stand-alone test methods should complete within a few minutes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:295
msgid ""
"Execution speed is important since these tests are intended to quickly "
"assess whether installed specs work on the system. Spack cannot spare "
"resources for more extensive testing of packages included in CI stacks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:298
msgid ""
"Consequently, stand-alone tests should run relatively quickly -- as in on "
"the order of at most a few minutes -- while testing at least key aspects of "
"the installed software. Save more extensive testing for other tools."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:301
msgid ""
"Tests are defined in the package using methods with names beginning "
"``test_``. This allows Spack to support multiple independent checks, or "
"parts. Files needed for testing, such as source, data, and expected outputs, "
"may be saved from the build and/or stored with the package in the "
"repository. Regardless of origin, these files are automatically copied to "
"the spec's test stage directory prior to execution of the test method(s). "
"Spack also provides helper functions to facilitate common processing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:309
msgid ""
"**The status of stand-alone tests can be used to guide follow-up testing "
"efforts.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:311
msgid ""
"Passing stand-alone tests justifies performing more thorough testing, such "
"as running extensive unit or regression tests or tests that run at scale, "
"when available. These tests are outside of the scope of Spack packaging."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:314
msgid ""
"Failing stand-alone tests indicate problems with the installation and, "
"therefore, no reason to proceed with more resource-intensive tests until the "
"failures have been investigated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:319
msgid "Configuring the test stage directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:321
msgid ""
"Stand-alone tests utilize a test stage directory to build, run, and track "
"tests in the same way Spack uses a build stage directory to install "
"software. The default test stage root directory, ``$HOME/.spack/test``, is "
"defined in :ref:`config.yaml <config-yaml>`. This location is customizable "
"by adding or changing the ``test_stage`` path such that:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:325
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  test_stage: /path/to/test/stage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:330
msgid ""
"Packages can use the ``self.test_suite.stage`` property to access the path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:332
msgid "Each spec being tested has its own test stage directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:334
msgid ""
"The ``config:test_stage`` option is the path to the root of a **test "
"suite**'s stage directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:336
msgid ""
"Other package properties that provide paths to spec-specific subdirectories "
"and files are described in :ref:`accessing-files`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:341
msgid "Adding stand-alone tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:343
msgid ""
"Test recipes are defined in the package using methods with names beginning "
"``test_``. This allows for the implementation of multiple independent tests. "
"Each method has access to the information Spack tracks on the package, such "
"as options, compilers, and dependencies, supporting the customization of "
"tests to the build. Standard Python ``assert`` statements and other error "
"reporting mechanisms can be used. These exceptions are automatically caught "
"and reported as test failures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:349
msgid ""
"Each test method is an *implicit test part* named by the method. Its purpose "
"is the method's docstring. Providing a meaningful purpose for the test gives "
"context that can aid debugging. Spack outputs both the name and purpose at "
"the start of test execution so it's also important that the docstring/"
"purpose be brief."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:356
msgid ""
"We recommend naming test methods so it is clear *what* is being tested. For "
"example, if a test method is building and/or running an executable called "
"``example``, then call the method ``test_example``. This, together with a "
"similarly meaningful test purpose, will aid test comprehension, debugging, "
"and maintainability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:360
msgid ""
"Stand-alone tests run in an environment that provides access to information "
"on the installed software, such as build options, dependencies, and "
"compilers. Build options and dependencies are accessed using the same spec "
"checks used by build recipes. Examples of checking :ref:`variant settings "
"<variants>` and :ref:`spec constraints <spec-objects>` can be found at the "
"provided links."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:364
msgid "Spack automatically sets up the test stage directory and environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:366
msgid ""
"Spack automatically creates the test stage directory and copies relevant "
"files *prior to* running tests. It can also ensure build dependencies are "
"available **if** necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:369
msgid ""
"The path to the test stage is configurable (see :ref:`configure-test-stage`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:371
msgid ""
"Files that Spack knows to copy are those saved from the build (see :ref:"
"`cache_extra_test_sources`) and those added to the package repository (see :"
"ref:`cache_custom_files`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:373
msgid ""
"Spack will use the value of the ``test_requires_compiler`` property to "
"determine whether it needs to also set up build dependencies (see :ref:`test-"
"build-tests`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:375
msgid ""
"The ``MyPackage`` package below provides two basic test examples: "
"``test_example`` and ``test_example2``. The first runs the installed "
"``example`` and ensures its output contains an expected string. The second "
"runs ``example2`` without checking output so is only concerned with "
"confirming the executable runs successfully. If the installed spec is not "
"expected to have ``example2``, then the check at the top of the method will "
"raise a special ``SkipTest`` exception, which is captured to facilitate "
"reporting skipped test parts to tools like CDash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:380
msgid ""
"class MyPackage(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    def test_example(self):\n"
"        \"\"\"ensure installed example works\"\"\"\n"
"        expected = \"Done.\"\n"
"        example = which(self.prefix.bin.example)\n"
"\n"
"        # Capture stdout and stderr from running the Executable\n"
"        # and check that the expected output was produced.\n"
"        out = example(output=str.split, error=str.split)\n"
"        assert expected in out, f\"Expected '{expected}' in the output\"\n"
"\n"
"    def test_example2(self):\n"
"        \"\"\"run installed example2\"\"\"\n"
"        if self.spec.satisfies(\"@:1.0\"):\n"
"            # Raise SkipTest to ensure flagging the test as skipped for\n"
"            # test reporting purposes.\n"
"            raise SkipTest(\"Test is only available for v1.1 on\")\n"
"\n"
"        example2 = which(self.prefix.bin.example2)\n"
"        example2()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:405
msgid ""
"Output showing the identification of each test part after running the tests "
"is illustrated below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:407
msgid ""
"$ spack test run --alias mypackage mypackage@2.0\n"
"==> Spack test mypackage\n"
"...\n"
"$ spack test results -l mypackage\n"
"==> Results for test suite 'mypackage':\n"
"...\n"
"==> [2024-03-10-16:03:56.625439] test: test_example: ensure installed "
"example works\n"
"...\n"
"PASSED: MyPackage::test_example\n"
"==> [2024-03-10-16:03:56.625439] test: test_example2: run installed "
"example2\n"
"...\n"
"PASSED: MyPackage::test_example2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:422
msgid "Do NOT implement tests that must run in the installation prefix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:424
msgid ""
"Use of the package spec's installation prefix for building and running tests "
"is **strongly discouraged**. Doing so causes permission errors for shared "
"spack instances *and* facilities that install the software in read-only file "
"systems or directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:427
msgid ""
"Instead, start these test methods by explicitly copying the needed files "
"from the installation prefix to the test stage directory. Note the test "
"stage directory is the current directory when the test is executed with the "
"``spack test run`` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:430
msgid "Test methods for library packages should build test executables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:432
msgid ""
"Stand-alone tests for library packages *should* build test executables that "
"utilize the *installed* library. Doing so ensures the tests follow a similar "
"build process that users of the library would follow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:435
msgid "For more information on how to do this, see :ref:`test-build-tests`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:439
msgid ""
"If you want to see more examples from packages with stand-alone tests, run "
"``spack pkg grep \"def\\stest\" | sed \"s/\\/package.py.*//g\" | sort -u`` "
"from the command line to get a list of the packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:444
msgid "Adding stand-alone test parts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:446
msgid ""
"Sometimes dependencies between steps of a test lend themselves to being "
"broken into parts. Tracking the pass/fail status of each part can aid "
"debugging. Spack provides a ``test_part`` context manager for use within "
"test methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:450
msgid ""
"Each test part is independently run, tracked, and reported. Test parts are "
"executed in the order they appear. If one fails, subsequent test parts are "
"still performed even if they would also fail. This allows tools like CDash "
"to track and report the status of test parts across runs. The pass/fail "
"status of the enclosing test is derived from the statuses of the embedded "
"test parts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:456
msgid "Test method and test part names **must** be unique."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:458
msgid ""
"Test results reporting requires that test methods and embedded test parts "
"within a package have unique names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:460
msgid "The signature for ``test_part`` is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:462
msgid ""
"def test_part(pkg, test_name, purpose, work_dir=\".\", verbose=False): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:466
#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:622
msgid "where each argument has the following meaning:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:468
#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:624
msgid "``pkg`` is an instance of the package for the spec under test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:470
msgid ""
"``test_name`` is the name of the test part, which must start with ``test_``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:472
msgid "``purpose`` is a brief description used as a heading for the test part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:474
msgid ""
"Output from the test is written to a test log file allowing the test name "
"and purpose to be searched for test part confirmation and debugging."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:476
msgid "``work_dir`` is the path to the directory in which the test will run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:478
msgid ""
"The default of ``None``, or ``\".\"``, corresponds to the spec's test stage "
"(i.e., ``self.test_suite.test_dir_for_spec(self.spec)``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:480
msgid "Start test part names with the name of the enclosing test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:482
msgid ""
"We **highly recommend** starting the names of test parts with the name of "
"the enclosing test. Doing so helps with the comprehension, readability and "
"debugging of test results."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:485
msgid ""
"Suppose ``MyPackage`` installs multiple executables that need to run in a "
"specific order since the outputs from one are inputs of others. Further "
"suppose we want to add an integration test that runs the executables in "
"order. We can accomplish this goal by implementing a stand-alone test method "
"consisting of test parts for each executable as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:489
msgid ""
"class MyPackage(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    def test_series(self):\n"
"        \"\"\"run setup, perform, and report\"\"\"\n"
"\n"
"        with test_part(self, \"test_series_setup\", purpose=\"setup "
"operation\"):\n"
"            exe = which(self.prefix.bin.setup)\n"
"            exe()\n"
"\n"
"        with test_part(self, \"test_series_run\", purpose=\"perform "
"operation\"):\n"
"            exe = which(self.prefix.bin.run)\n"
"            exe()\n"
"\n"
"        with test_part(self, \"test_series_report\", purpose=\"generate "
"report\"):\n"
"            exe = which(self.prefix.bin.report)\n"
"            exe()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:509
msgid ""
"The result is ``test_series`` runs the following executable in order: "
"``setup``, ``run``, and ``report``. In this case no options are passed to "
"any of the executables and no outputs from running them are checked. "
"Consequently, the implementation could be simplified with a for-loop as "
"follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:513
msgid ""
"class MyPackage(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    def test_series(self):\n"
"        \"\"\"execute series setup, run, and report\"\"\"\n"
"\n"
"        for exe, reason in [\n"
"            (\"setup\", \"setup operation\"),\n"
"            (\"run\", \"perform operation\"),\n"
"            (\"report\", \"generate report\"),\n"
"        ]:\n"
"            with test_part(self, f\"test_series_{exe}\", purpose=reason):\n"
"                exe = which(self.prefix.bin.join(exe))\n"
"                exe()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:530
msgid ""
"In both cases, since we're using a context manager, each test part in "
"``test_series`` will execute regardless of the status of the other test "
"parts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:532
msgid ""
"Now let's look at the output from running the stand-alone tests where the "
"second test part, ``test_series_run``, fails."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:534
msgid ""
"$ spack test run --alias mypackage mypackage@1.0\n"
"==> Spack test mypackage\n"
"...\n"
"$ spack test results -l mypackage\n"
"==> Results for test suite 'mypackage':\n"
"...\n"
"==> [2024-03-10-16:03:56.625204] test: test_series: execute series setup, "
"run, and report\n"
"==> [2024-03-10-16:03:56.625439] test: test_series_setup: setup operation\n"
"...\n"
"PASSED: MyPackage::test_series_setup\n"
"==> [2024-03-10-16:03:56.625555] test: test_series_run: perform operation\n"
"...\n"
"FAILED: MyPackage::test_series_run\n"
"==> [2024-03-10-16:03:57.003456] test: test_series_report: generate report\n"
"...\n"
"FAILED: MyPackage::test_series_report\n"
"FAILED: MyPackage::test_series\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:555
msgid ""
"Since test parts depended on the success of previous parts, we see that the "
"failure of one results in the failure of subsequent checks and the overall "
"result of the test method, ``test_series``, is failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:559
msgid ""
"If you want to see more examples from packages using ``test_part``, run "
"``spack pkg grep \"test_part(\" | sed \"s/\\/package.py.*//g\" | sort -u`` "
"from the command line to get a list of the packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:564
msgid "Building and running test executables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:566
msgid "Reuse build-time sources and (small) input data sets when possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:568
msgid ""
"We **highly recommend** reusing build-time test sources and pared down input "
"files for testing installed software. These files are easier to keep "
"synchronized with software capabilities when they reside within the "
"software's repository. More information on saving files from the "
"installation process can be found at :ref:`cache_extra_test_sources`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:572
msgid ""
"If that is not possible, you can add test-related files to the package "
"repository (see :ref:`cache_custom_files`). It will be important to remember "
"to maintain them so they work across listed or supported versions of the "
"package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:575
msgid ""
"Packages that build libraries are good examples of cases where you'll want "
"to build test executables from the installed software before running them. "
"Doing so requires you to let Spack know it needs to load the package's "
"compiler configuration. This is accomplished by setting the package's "
"``test_requires_compiler`` property to ``True``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:579
msgid ""
"``test_requires_compiler = True`` is required to build test executables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:581
msgid ""
"Setting the property to ``True`` ensures access to the compiler through "
"canonical environment variables (e.g., ``CC``, ``CXX``, ``FC``, ``F77``). It "
"also gives access to build dependencies like ``cmake`` through their ``spec "
"objects`` (e.g., ``self.spec[\"cmake\"].prefix.bin.cmake`` for the path or "
"``self.spec[\"cmake\"].command`` for the ``Executable`` instance)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:584
msgid ""
"Be sure to add the property at the top of the package class under other "
"properties like the ``homepage``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:586
msgid ""
"The example below, which ignores how ``cxx-example.cpp`` is acquired, "
"illustrates the basic process of compiling a test executable using the "
"installed library before running it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:588
msgid ""
"class MyLibrary(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    test_requires_compiler = True\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    def test_cxx_example(self):\n"
"        \"\"\"build and run cxx-example\"\"\"\n"
"        exe = \"cxx-example\"\n"
"        ...\n"
"        cxx = which(os.environ[\"CXX\"])\n"
"        cxx(f\"-L{self.prefix.lib}\", f\"-I{self.prefix.include}\", f\"{exe}."
"cpp\", \"-o\", exe)\n"
"        cxx_example = which(exe)\n"
"        cxx_example()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:605
msgid ""
"Typically the files used to build and/or run test executables are either "
"cached from the installation (see :ref:`cache_extra_test_sources`) or added "
"to the package repository (see :ref:`cache_custom_files`). There is nothing "
"preventing the use of both."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:611
msgid "Saving build- and install-time files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:613
msgid ""
"You can use the ``cache_extra_test_sources`` helper routine to copy "
"directories and/or files from the source build stage directory to the "
"package's installation directory. Spack will automatically copy these files "
"for you when it sets up the test stage directory and before it begins "
"running the tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:616
msgid "The signature for ``cache_extra_test_sources`` is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:618
msgid "def cache_extra_test_sources(pkg, srcs): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:626
msgid ""
"``srcs`` is a string *or* a list of strings corresponding to the paths of "
"subdirectories and/or files needed for stand-alone testing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:630
msgid ""
"Paths provided in the ``srcs`` argument **must be relative** to the staged "
"source directory. They will be copied to the equivalent relative location "
"under the test stage directory prior to test execution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:633
msgid ""
"Contents of subdirectories and files are copied to a special test cache "
"subdirectory of the installation prefix. They are automatically copied to "
"the appropriate relative paths under the test stage directory prior to "
"executing stand-alone tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:638
msgid "*Perform test-related conversions once when copying files.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:640
msgid ""
"If one or more of the copied files needs to be modified to reference the "
"installed software, it is recommended that those changes be made to the "
"cached files **once** in the post-``install`` copy method **after** the call "
"to ``cache_extra_test_sources``. This will reduce the amount of unnecessary "
"work in the test method **and** avoid problems running stand-alone tests in "
"shared instances and facility deployments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:643
msgid ""
"The ``filter_file`` function can be quite useful for such changes (see :ref:"
"`file-filtering`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:645
msgid ""
"Below is a basic example of a test that relies on files from the "
"installation. This package method reuses the contents of the ``examples`` "
"subdirectory, which is assumed to have all of the files necessary to allow "
"``make`` to compile and link ``foo.c`` and ``bar.c`` against the package's "
"installed library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:648
msgid ""
"class MyLibPackage(MakefilePackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    @run_after(\"install\")\n"
"    def copy_test_files(self):\n"
"        cache_extra_test_sources(self, \"examples\")\n"
"\n"
"    def test_example(self):\n"
"        \"\"\"build and run the examples\"\"\"\n"
"        examples_dir = self.test_suite.current_test_cache_dir.examples\n"
"        with working_dir(examples_dir):\n"
"            make = which(\"make\")\n"
"            make()\n"
"\n"
"            for program in [\"foo\", \"bar\"]:\n"
"                with test_part(self, f\"test_example_{program}\", "
"purpose=f\"ensure {program} runs\"):\n"
"                    exe = Executable(program)\n"
"                    exe()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:669
msgid ""
"In this case, ``copy_test_files`` copies the associated files from the build "
"stage to the package's test cache directory under the installation prefix. "
"Running ``spack test run`` for the package results in Spack copying the "
"directory and its contents to the test stage directory. The ``working_dir`` "
"context manager ensures the commands within it are executed from the "
"``examples_dir``. The test builds the software using ``make`` before running "
"each executable, ``foo`` and ``bar``, as independent test parts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:676
msgid ""
"The method name ``copy_test_files`` here is for illustration purposes. You "
"are free to use a name that is better suited to your package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:679
msgid ""
"The key to copying files for stand-alone testing at build time is use of the "
"``run_after`` directive, which ensures the associated files are copied "
"**after** the provided build stage (``install``) when the installation "
"prefix **and** files are available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:681
msgid ""
"The test method uses the path contained in the package's ``self.test_suite."
"current_test_cache_dir`` property for the root directory of the copied "
"files. In this case, that's the ``examples`` subdirectory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:686
msgid ""
"If you want to see more examples from packages that cache build files, run "
"``spack pkg grep cache_extra_test_sources | sed \"s/\\/package.py.*//g\" | "
"sort -u`` from the command line to get a list of the packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:691
msgid "Adding custom files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:693
msgid ""
"Sometimes it is helpful or necessary to include custom files for building "
"and/or checking the results of tests as part of the package. Examples of the "
"types of files that might be useful are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:696
msgid "test source files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:697
msgid "test input files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:698
msgid "test build scripts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:699
msgid "expected test outputs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:701
msgid ""
"While obtaining such files from the software repository is preferred (see :"
"ref:`cache_extra_test_sources`), there are circumstances where doing so is "
"not feasible such as when the software is not being actively maintained. "
"When test files cannot be obtained from the repository or there is a need to "
"supplement files that can, Spack supports the inclusion of additional files "
"under the ``test`` subdirectory of the package in the Spack repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:704
msgid ""
"The following example assumes a ``custom-example.c`` is saved in "
"``MyLibrary`` package's ``test`` subdirectory. It also assumes the program "
"simply needs to be compiled and linked against the installed ``MyLibrary`` "
"software."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:707
msgid ""
"class MyLibrary(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    test_requires_compiler = True\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    def test_custom_example(self):\n"
"        \"\"\"build and run custom-example\"\"\"\n"
"        src_dir = self.test_suite.current_test_data_dir\n"
"        exe = \"custom-example\"\n"
"\n"
"        with working_dir(src_dir):\n"
"            cc = which(os.environ[\"CC\"])\n"
"            cc(f\"-L{self.prefix.lib}\", f\"-I{self.prefix.include}\", "
"f\"{exe}.cpp\", \"-o\", exe)\n"
"\n"
"            custom_example = Executable(exe)\n"
"            custom_example()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:727
msgid ""
"In this case, ``spack test run`` for the package results in Spack copying "
"the contents of the ``test`` subdirectory to the test stage directory path "
"in ``self.test_suite.current_test_data_dir`` before calling "
"``test_custom_example``. Use of the ``working_dir`` context manager ensures "
"the commands to build and run the program are performed from within the "
"appropriate subdirectory of the test stage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:733
msgid "Reading expected output from a file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:735
msgid ""
"The helper function ``get_escaped_text_output`` is available for packages to "
"retrieve properly formatted text from a file potentially containing special "
"characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:737
msgid "The signature for ``get_escaped_text_output`` is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:739
msgid "def get_escaped_text_output(filename): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:743
msgid ""
"where ``filename`` is the path to the file containing the expected output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:745
msgid ""
"The path provided to ``filename`` for one of the copied custom files (:ref:"
"`custom file <cache_custom_files>`) is in the path rooted at ``self."
"test_suite.current_test_data_dir``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:747
msgid ""
"The example below shows how to reference both the custom database "
"(``packages.db``) and expected output (``dump.out``) files Spack copies to "
"the test stage:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:749
msgid ""
"import re\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class Sqlite(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    def test_example(self):\n"
"        \"\"\"check example table dump\"\"\"\n"
"        test_data_dir = self.test_suite.current_test_data_dir\n"
"        db_filename = test_data_dir.join(\"packages.db\")\n"
"        ...\n"
"        expected = get_escaped_text_output(test_data_dir.join(\"dump."
"out\"))\n"
"        sqlite3 = which(self.prefix.bin.sqlite3)\n"
"        out = sqlite3(db_filename, \".dump\", output=str.split, error=str."
"split)\n"
"        for exp in expected:\n"
"            assert re.search(exp, out), f\"Expected '{exp}' in output\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:768
msgid ""
"If the files were instead cached from installing the software, the paths to "
"the two files would be found under the ``self.test_suite."
"current_test_cache_dir`` directory as shown below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:770
msgid ""
"def test_example(self):\n"
"    \"\"\"check example table dump\"\"\"\n"
"    test_cache_dir = self.test_suite.current_test_cache_dir\n"
"    db_filename = test_cache_dir.join(\"packages.db\")\n"
"    ...\n"
"    expected = get_escaped_text_output(test_cache_dir.join(\"dump.out\"))\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:780
msgid ""
"Alternatively, if both files had been installed by the software into the "
"``share/tests`` subdirectory of the installation prefix, the paths to the "
"two files would be referenced as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:782
msgid ""
"def test_example(self):\n"
"    \"\"\"check example table dump\"\"\"\n"
"    db_filename = self.prefix.share.tests.join(\"packages.db\")\n"
"    ...\n"
"    expected = get_escaped_text_output(self.prefix.share.tests.join(\"dump."
"out\"))\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:794
msgid "Comparing expected to actual outputs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:796
msgid ""
"The ``check_outputs`` helper routine is available for packages to ensure "
"multiple expected outputs from running an executable are contained within "
"the actual outputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:798
msgid "The signature for ``check_outputs`` is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:800
msgid "def check_outputs(expected, actual): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:804
msgid "where each argument has the expected type and meaning:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:806
msgid ""
"``expected`` is a string or list of strings containing the expected (raw) "
"output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:808
msgid ""
"``actual`` is a string containing the actual output from executing the "
"command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:810
msgid "Invoking the method is the equivalent of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:812
msgid ""
"errors = []\n"
"for check in expected:\n"
"    if not re.search(check, actual):\n"
"        errors.append(f\"Expected '{check}' in output '{actual}'\")\n"
"if errors:\n"
"    raise RuntimeError(\"\\n \".join(errors))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_testing.rst:823
msgid ""
"If you want to see more examples from packages that use this helper, run "
"``spack pkg grep check_outputs | sed \"s/\\/package.py.*//g\" | sort -u`` "
"from the command line to get a list of the packages."
msgstr ""

